CURVATURE–MEMORY COSMOLOGY
A Cumulative Stiffness Framework for Late-Time Expansion

Martin Ollett
2026


Abstract
--------

We present a cosmological framework in which the late-time expansion of the Universe is governed by the cumulative response of the matter–radiation sector to curvature history. The model introduces a stiffness-memory variable that accumulates curvature information across cosmic time and modulates the effective participation of matter in the Friedmann equation.

The background expansion emerges through a nonlinear saturation map applied to the accumulated memory field. The resulting cosmology admits a compact autonomous formulation, a curvature-history identity relating the memory field to the Ricci scalar of the source background, and a localized auxiliary-field representation on FLRW spacetimes.

We derive the low-redshift cosmographic structure of the model and show that the observable parameters (q₀, j₀) and the effective equation-of-state parameter w_eff,0 obey exact algebraic relations. The parameter-to-observable map becomes singular only along a single curve in parameter space and remains regular within the physically admissible late-time corridor.

The framework therefore defines a constrained cosmographic surface rather than a generic two-parameter expansion history and provides a mathematically compact description of curvature-memory driven cosmic acceleration.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Introduction
---------------

Standard ΛCDM cosmology attributes the late-time acceleration of the Universe to a constant vacuum energy density. While the model successfully reproduces a wide range of observations, it leaves open the question of whether the accelerated expansion could arise from dynamical properties of the gravitational sector itself.

The curvature-memory framework explores the possibility that the expansion rate responds not only to instantaneous matter density but also to accumulated curvature history. In such a picture the effective gravitational participation of matter evolves with cosmic time as curvature information is integrated along the expansion trajectory.

The goal of this work is to formulate a minimal realization of this idea at the background level and to derive its observable consequences.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

2. Cumulative Stiffness Variable
--------------------------------

In the spatial Motion–TimeSpace formulation the observable gravitational response is governed by accumulated stiffness distance

    χ(r) = ∫₀ʳ m(s) ds.

Across spatial tests including Yukawa systems, stochastic density fields, and disk–halo models, the observable response appears as a saturating function of this cumulative variable.

Motivated by this structure we introduce a cosmological analogue

    Ξ(z) = ∫₀ᶻ μ(ζ) dζ,

where μ(z) is an effective cosmological stiffness kernel.

The quantity Ξ(z) represents the accumulated stiffness memory between the present epoch and redshift z.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

3. Saturating Response Law
--------------------------

Spatial analyses of the stiffness framework exhibit exponential saturation

    R(χ) = 1 − e^(−χ).

We adopt the same structure for the cosmological response

    g(z) = 1 − e^(−Ξ(z)).

The background expansion becomes

    H²(z) =
        H₀² [
            Ω_m (1+z)³ g(z)
            + Ω_r (1+z)⁴
            + Ω_Λ
        ].

Thus the matter contribution to the Friedmann equation is modulated by the participation factor g(z).


---------------------------------------------------------------------

4. Self-Similar Stiffness Kernel
--------------------------------

A minimal closure for the stiffness kernel is a power-law accumulation

    μ(z) ∝ z^(ν−1).

Integrating gives

    Ξ(z) = (z / z_t)^ν.

The participation function becomes

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − (z / z_t)^ν ].


---------------------------------------------------------------------

5. Source Background and Memory Field
-------------------------------------

Define the source background

    E_src²(z) =
        Ω_m (1+z)³
        + Ω_r (1+z)⁴
        + Ω_Λ.

Introduce the logarithmic expansion variable

    N = ln a.

The memory field is defined as

    M(N) = A ln E_src(N).

The response function becomes

    g(N) = 1 − e^(−M(N)).

The observable expansion branch is

    E²(N) =
        [m(N) + r(N)] g(N)
        + Ω_Λ.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

6. Curvature-History Identity
-----------------------------

For a flat FLRW spacetime

    R / H² = 6 (2 + d ln E / dN).

Applying this to the source background gives

    M' =
        (A/6) [ R_src / H_src² − 12 ].

Thus the memory field evolves linearly with the curvature history of the source expansion.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

7. Autonomous System
--------------------

Define

    u = m / (m + r + Ω_Λ)
    v = r / (m + r + Ω_Λ).

The system reduces to

    u' = u[ −3 + (3u + 4v) ]

    v' = v[ −4 + (3u + 4v) ]

    M' = − (A/2)(3u + 4v)

    g = 1 − e^(−M).


---------------------------------------------------------------------

8. Late-Time Reduction
----------------------

When radiation becomes negligible (v << 1)

    u' ≈ 3u(u − 1)

    M' ≈ − (3A/2) u.

Integrating gives

    M(u) ≈ − (A/2) ln(1 − u) + C.

The response law becomes

    g(u) ≈ 1 − B (1 − u)^(A/2).


---------------------------------------------------------------------

9. Linear Growth of Structure
-----------------------------

The linear density perturbation equation becomes

    δ'' +
    (2 + d ln H / d ln a) δ'
    − (3/2) Ω_m(a) g(z) δ
    = 0.

At early times

    g(z) → 1

recovering standard growth.

At late times

    g(z) < 1

suppressing gravitational clustering.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

10. Cosmographic Expansion
--------------------------

Expanding around z = 0 gives

    E²(z) =
        Ω_Λ
        + (3A Ω_m² / 2) z
        + [ 6A Ω_m²
            − (9A Ω_m³)/4
            − (9A² Ω_m³)/8 ] z²
        + O(z³).

The present deceleration parameter becomes

    q₀ = −1 + (3A Ω_m²)/(4(1 − Ω_m)).

The jerk parameter is

    j₀ =
        1 +
        (9A Ω_m² / [8(1 − Ω_m)])
        [4 − (A + 2) Ω_m].


---------------------------------------------------------------------

11. Inverse Cosmographic Map
----------------------------

The memory parameter can be reconstructed from q₀:

    A =
        [4(1 − Ω_m) / (3 Ω_m²)] (q₀ + 1).

Substituting into the jerk relation yields

    j₀ =
        1
        + 3(2 − Ω_m)(q₀ + 1)
        − 2[(1 − Ω_m)/Ω_m](q₀ + 1)².

Thus for fixed Ω_m the model traces a quadratic curve in the (q₀, j₀) plane.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

12. Effective Equation of State
-------------------------------

Eliminating A yields

    w_eff,0 =
        (1 − Ω_m)(2q₀ − 1) / [3(1 − 2Ω_m)].

Thus the present effective equation of state is algebraically tied to q₀.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

13. Jacobian and Degeneracy
---------------------------

The Jacobian of the map (A, Ω_m) → (q₀, j₀) has determinant

    det =
        [27 A Ω_m⁴ / (32 (1 − Ω_m)³)]
        [A − 2(1 − Ω_m)].

The map becomes singular on

    A = 2(1 − Ω_m).


---------------------------------------------------------------------

14. Physical Corridor
---------------------

If the admissibility conditions

    0 < Ω_m < 1/2
    A > 2

are imposed, then

    det > 0

and the observable map remains locally invertible.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

15. Cumulative Stiffness–Memory Equivalence
-------------------------------------------

The cumulative stiffness variable

    Ξ(z) = ∫ μ(z) dz

is equivalent to the logarithmic memory field.

Differentiating

    M(z) = A ln E_src(z)

gives

    dM/dz =
        A (1 / E_src) dE_src/dz.

Define

    μ(z) =
        A (1 / E_src) dE_src/dz.

Then

    M(z) = ∫ μ(z) dz.

Thus

    Ξ(z) = M(z) = A ln E_src(z).

The response function becomes

    g(z) = 1 − e^(−Ξ(z))
         = 1 − E_src^(−A).

The observable expansion branch therefore becomes

    E²(z) =
        Ω_m (1+z)³ [1 − E_src^(−A)]
        + Ω_Λ.


---------------------------------------------------------------------

16. Interpretation
------------------

The curvature-memory cosmology can be summarized as a three-stage system

    source expansion
        → curvature-history memory
        → nonlinear response
        → modified expansion branch

        E_src
            → Ξ = A ln E_src
            → g = 1 − e^(−Ξ)
            → E(z).

Thus the cumulative stiffness kernel and the sourced-memory formulation
represent the same dynamical structure expressed in different variables.


